{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656008"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:08:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:08:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18707"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18707"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.76,0.04,0.08,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11439"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76943"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11439"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18707"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62448"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26486"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26491"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76943"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe fallopian tubes play a crucial role in human reproduction by facilitating the transport of gametes and providing an environment for fertilisation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how an ovum travels through the fallopian tube?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Active transport using ATP-dependent proteins","Coordinated ciliary beating and muscle contractions","Osmotic flow of tubal fluid","Gravity-dependent flow towards the uterus","Passive diffusion along a pressure gradient"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ovum travels through the fallopian tube via \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoordinated ciliary beating and muscle contractions\u003C/strong\u003E. The fallopian tube epithelium contains ciliated cells that beat in a coordinated fashion towards the uterus. This action, combined with peristaltic contractions of the smooth muscle in the tubal wall, propels the ovum along the tube.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive diffusion along a pressure gradient\u003C/strong\u003E - No significant pressure gradient exists in the fallopian tube to drive ovum movement\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport using ATP-dependent proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - The ovum is too large for protein-mediated transport\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGravity-dependent flow towards the uterus\u003C/strong\u003E - The fallopian tubes are positioned such that gravity does not significantly influence transport\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsmotic flow of tubal fluid\u003C/strong\u003E - While tubal fluid is important for maintaining the environment, osmotic flow does not drive ovum transport\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis transport mechanism ensures controlled movement of the ovum, allowing sufficient time for potential fertilisation and early embryo development while maintaining the appropriate physiological environment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The fallopian tubes contain ciliated epithelial cells that move the ovum towards the uterus through coordinated beating.","Smooth muscle in the fallopian tube wall creates peristaltic movements that help transport the ovum.","The fallopian tube environment provides essential nutrients and factors for fertilisation and early embryo development."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62448"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18707"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62448"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T20:43:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T20:43:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11439"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76943"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co